The '''Applied Technology Council''' is a nonprofit research organization based in California which studies the effects of [[natural hazard]]s on the built environment and how to mitigate these effects, particularly [[earthquake]]s. It was founded through the efforts of the [[National Council of Structural Engineers Associations|Structural Engineers Association of California]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.atcouncil.org/about-atc |title=About ATC |website=Applied Technology Council}}</ref> It does not develop [[building code]]s but does develop manuals which summarize information for engineers, and this information is sometimes used in codes, standards, and specifications.<ref>{{cite book |date=May 1999 |title=Repair of Earthquake Damaged Concrete and Masonry Wall Buildings (FEMA 308) |url=http://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1453-20490-4004/fema-308.pdf |publisher=[[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] |page=53 |isbn=978-1484111369}}</ref>

